</DisplayEquation>


</SubSubSection>

<SubSubSection title="Fasteners" id="fasteners">
<p>
<strong>Fasteners</strong> supply resistance at fixed intervals. Use the shear flow formula to analyze the beam.
</p>

<strong>Example:</strong> The followling beams are composed of two boards nailed together with 6 nails at an interval of <InlineEquation equation="\\Delta s = 50 \\text{ } mm"/>. The shear force is <InlineEquation equation="V = 100 \\text{ } kN"/>. 
Find the shear flow (<InlineEquation equation="q"/>) and the load each fastener carries (<InlineEquation equation="f_n"/>).

<Image src="/Solid_Mechanics/TransverseShear-Figures/FastenerExample.png" width="5.5"></Image>

<DisplayEquation equation="\\begin{align*} &q = \\frac{VQ}{I},\\  &f_n = \\frac{q*s_{total}}{4}\\ \\end{align*}" title="Shear flow in fasteners" background="True" derivation="True" id="fsn-exp">

  <Image src="/Solid_Mechanics/TransverseShear-Figures/BoardsQ.png" width="2"></Image>

  <DisplayEquation equation="Q = (b*h)\\bar{y} = 3.75*10^5 \\text{ } mm^3" />

  <DisplayEquation equation="I = \\frac{1}{12}b h^3 = 2.5*10^7 \\text{ } mm^4" />

  <DisplayEquation equation="q = 1.5 \\text{ } \\frac{kN}{mm}" />


  <DisplayEquation equation="\\Sigma F_{total} = \\frac{1}{2}f_n + f_n + \\frac{1}{2}f_n = 2f_n" />
  
  Because there are 2 nails in each row, 

  <DisplayEquation equation="\\Sigma F_{total} = 2*F_{total} = 2*2f_n = 4f_n" />

  <DisplayEquation equation="s_{total} = 2\\Delta s = 100 \\text{ } mm^4" />

  <DisplayEquation equation="f_n = 37.5 \\text{ } kN" />




</DisplayEquation>


